      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, and honestly, it's exactly what a lot of student loan borrowers experience, but I can tell you that your situation is actually quite normal, though it might feel like the loans are hiding from you like a shy goblin in the corner of your mind.\n\nHere is the breakdown: when you make that monthly payment, the very first chunk of it goes toward interest, not principal. Since your interest rate is calculated daily based on the remaining balance, the bank is essentially charging you a fee for borrowing the money, and that fee is eating up most of your fixed payment.\n\nThink of it like a goblin trying to steal your lunch money every day. If you give the goblin a fixed amount of gold coins every day, he will take almost all of it to feed his little green belly, leaving you with almost nothing to actually pay off the debt. Only once the balance drops significantly enough that the daily interest charge becomes smaller will your payment start chipping away more aggressively at the principal.\n\nSo, don't panic! It's not that your payments are ineffective; it's just that the interest is currently acting like a very efficient goblin, devouring the bulk of your contribution. As long as",
